The '''Tesla Model X''' is a [[Battery electric vehicle|battery electric]] [[Mid-size crossover SUV#Luxury|mid-size luxury crossover SUV]] built by [[Tesla, Inc.]] since 2015. Developed from the [[full-size car|full-sized sedan]] platform of the [[Tesla Model S]], the vehicle notably uses [[falcon wing doors]] for passenger access.

The Model X has an [[United States Environmental Protection Agency|EPA]] size class as an [[Sport utility vehicle|SUV]],<ref name="ModelX90EPA">{{cite web|url=http://www.fueleconomy.gov/feg/Find.do?action=sbs&id=36979&id=36980|title=2016 Tesla Model X AWD – 90D and P90D, Fuel economy and specs|author=[[U. S. Environmental Protection Agency]] and [[U.S. Department of Energy]]|date=September 26, 2015|access-date=October 3, 2015}}</ref> and shares around 30 percent of its content with the Model S, half of the originally planned 60 percent, and weighs about 10 percent more. Both the Model X and Model S are produced at the [[Tesla Factory]] in [[Fremont, California]]. The [[concept car|prototype]] was unveiled at Tesla's design studios in [[Hawthorne, California]] on February 9, 2012.<ref name="NYT020912">{{cite news|last=Garrett|first=Jerry|url=http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/02/09/tesla-unveils-model-x-at-its-design-studios/|title=Tesla Unveils Model X at Its Southern California Design Studios|date=February 9, 2012|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=February 10, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Evans|first=Huw|url=http://www.hybridcars.com/tesla-reveals-model-x-prototype-36391/|title=Tesla Reveals Model X Prototype|date=February 10, 2012|access-date=February 10, 2012|website=HybridCars.com}}</ref> First deliveries of the Model X began in September 2015.<ref name="ModelXfirst" /> After one full year on the market, in 2016, the Model X ranked seventh among the world's best-selling plug-in cars.<ref name="Top10PEVs2016" /> A refresh of the Tesla Model X was introduced in 2021, offering a new "Plaid" performance model, along with a revised interior, powertrain, and suspension.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Tesla Model X facelift: new interior and 1,006bhp Plaid model for 2021 |url=https://www.autoexpress.co.uk/news/354161/tesla-model-x-facelift-new-interior-and-1006bhp-plaid-model-2021 |access-date=2023-07-10 |website=Auto Express |language=en}}</ref>

{{As of|2023|9}}, the Model X is available as a Long-Range version with an estimated EPA range of {{Convert|348|mi}} and a high performance "Plaid" version with an estimated EPA range of {{Convert|333|mi}}.

== History ==
Initially, Tesla planned for deliveries to commence in early 2014.<ref>{{cite web |title=Geneva show: Tesla Model X |url=http://www.autocar.co.uk/www.autocar.co.uk/News/NewsArticle/AllCars/261282/ |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120719161901/http://www.autocar.co.uk/www.autocar.co.uk/News/NewsArticle/AllCars/261282/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 19, 2012 |website=Autocar |access-date=March 14, 2013 }}</ref> However, in February 2013, the company announced that deliveries had been rescheduled to begin by late 2014 in order to achieve its production target of 20,000 [[Tesla Model S|Model S]] cars in 2013.<ref name=LAT032013>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/autos/la-fi-hy-tesla-to-repay-federal-loans-five-years-early-20130308,0,5843577.story|title=Tesla plans to repay loans early, delays Model X|author=Ronald D. White|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=March 8, 2013|access-date=March 10, 2013}}</ref>  In November 2013, Tesla said it expected to begin Model X high volume production the second quarter of 2015.<ref name=IBTimes112013>{{cite news |last=Young|first=Angelo|title=Tesla Model X Release Date: Superficial Production Next Year; Deliveries To Customers In Full Effect Later|url= http://www.ibtimes.com/tesla-model-x-release-date-superficial-production-next-year-deliveries-customers-full-effect-later |newspaper=[[International Business Times]]|date=November 6, 2013|access-date=January 1, 2014}}</ref> In November 2014, Tesla again delayed and announced that Model X deliveries would begin in the third quarter of 2015.<ref name=Deliveries3Q2015>{{cite web|url=http://green.autoblog.com/2014/11/05/tesla-model-x-delayed-again/|title=Tesla Model X delayed, again, but Musk says Model S demand remains high |author=Sebastian Blanco|publisher=Autoblog Green |date=November 5, 2014|access-date=November 5, 2014}}</ref> Deliveries began on September 29, 2015. Among the reasons for delay were problems with the falcon-wing doors and cooling the motors when hauling trailers.<ref name=gcr022015>{{cite news |first=John |last=Voelcker |url=http://www.greencarreports.com/news/1096685_why-tesla-model-x-electric-suv-is-late-range-towing-falcon-doors/page-2 |title=Why Tesla Model X Electric SUV Is Late: Range, Towing, 'Falcon Doors'  |website=Green Car Reports |date=February 9, 2015|access-date=April 8, 2015}}</ref>

In 2016, the company filed a [[lawsuit]] against Swiss hydraulics firm [[Hoerbiger Holding]] for not producing satisfactory falcon-wing doors for the Model X. Tesla claimed the doors suffered from oil leakage and overheating. Many believe this is one of the reasons for the delay of the Model X.<ref name=ab20160126>{{cite news |title=Tesla sues Model X falcon wing door supplier |url=http://www.autoblog.com/2016/01/25/tesla-model-x-falcon-wing-supplier-lawsuit/ |website=Autoblog |date=January 26, 2016 |access-date=February 13, 2016 }}</ref> The lawsuit was settled in September 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://electrek.co/2016/09/27/tesla-settles-in-court-with-supplier-over-the-development-of-the-model-xs-falcon-wing-doors/ |title=Tesla settles court case with supplier over the development of the Model X's Falcon Wing doors|website=Electrek|date=September 27, 2016|access-date=September 27, 2016}}</ref>

On July 13, 2016, Tesla introduced its Model X 60D, which is slightly lower priced than the Model X's starting price. The Model X 60D has a {{cvt|200|mi|km}} range and can accelerate from {{cvt|0|to|60|mph}} in 6 seconds, with a top speed of {{cvt|130|mph}}.<ref>{{Citation |url=https://www.caranddriver.com/news/lowercase-x-tesla-launches-lower-priced-model-x-60d |title= Lowercase x: Tesla Launches Lower-Priced Model X 60D |date=July 13, 2016 |first=Bengt |last=Halvorson |magazine=[[Car and Driver]] }}</ref> The battery capacity in the Model X 60D is 75&nbsp;kWh but has been software restricted to 60&nbsp;kWh. Post purchase, owners have the option to unlock the additional 15&nbsp;kWh, bringing the 60D to 75D range specifications.<ref>Mark Lelinwalla, TechCrunch. "[https://techcrunch.com/2016/07/13/tesla-introduces-a-more-affordable-model-x/ Tesla introduces a more affordable Model X]." July 13, 2016.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://insideevs.com/tesla-model-x-60d-upgrade-75d-now-just-4500/|title=Tesla Model X 60D Upgrade To 75D Now Just $4,500|date=2017-04-27|website=Inside EVs|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-28}}</ref><!--Hardware is 75kWh; software is restricted to 60kWh.-->

Global sales passed the 10,000 unit mark in August 2016, with most cars delivered in the United States.<ref name = ModelX10K /> In August 2016, Tesla introduced the P100D with Ludicrous Mode to be the new top Model X. The P100D has a 100&nbsp;kWh battery, accelerate from {{cvt|0|to|60|mph}} in 2.9 seconds ({{cvt|0|to|100|kph}} in 3.1 seconds) and {{cvt|289|mi}} of range.<ref>[https://electrek.co/2016/08/23/tesla-100-kwh-battery-pack-quickest-car-ever/ Tesla claims 'Quickest Production Car in the World' title with new 100 kWh battery pack: 0–60 in 2.5s & 315 mile range] Electrek, August 23, 2016.</ref> In October 2016 Tesla discontinued the 60D version and made the "Smart Air Suspension" standard instead of coil springs, increasing the base price to $85,000.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://electrek.co/2016/10/07/tesla-increases-base-price-model-x-smart-air-suspension-standard/ |title=Tesla increases base price of the Model X by making the 'Smart Air Suspension' standard|date= October 7, 2016 |website=Electrek |access-date=October 7, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://electrek.co/2016/10/08/tesla-discontinues-model-x-60d/ |title=Tesla discontinues the Model X 60D with software-limited 75 kWh battery pack|date= October 8, 2016 |website=Electrek |access-date=October 8, 2016}}</ref> In June 2017, the 90D version was discontinued.

In August 2017, Tesla announced that HW2.5 included a secondary processor node to provide more computing power and additional wiring redundancy to slightly improve reliability; it also enabled dashcam and sentry mode capabilities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tesla.com/support/software-v9#dashcam|title=Discover Software Version 9.0|date=2018-10-05|website=www.tesla.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-21|quote="Dashcam is only available for Model S and Model X cars manufactured after August 2017..."}}</ref><ref name=":7">{{cite web|last1=Lambert|first1=Frederic|title=Tesla has a new Autopilot '2.5' hardware suite with more computing power for autonomous driving|url=https://electrek.co/2017/08/09/tesla-autopilot-2-5-hardware-computer-autonomous-driving/|publisher=electrek.co|access-date=15 February 2018|date=August 9, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Hawkins|first1=Andrew|title=Tesla has been working on a backup plan in case its self-driving promises fail|url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/8/9/16119746/tesla-self-driving-hardware-upgrade-hw-2-5|website=The Verge|date=August 9, 2017|access-date=15 February 2018}}</ref>

In March 2018 it was announced that Tesla upgraded the MCU to version 2.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-model-s-x-mcu-upgrade-faster-display/|title=Tesla Model S/X gets updated MCU for faster, more responsive touchscreen display|last=Alvarez|first=Simon|date=2018-03-14|website=TESLARATI|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-21}}</ref>  MCU 2 improved the performance of the 17 inch center console screen.

Global cumulative sales since inception totaled 106,689 units through September 2018.<ref name=Top10PEVs2016 /><ref name=Tesla1Q2017 /><ref name=Tesla2Q2017 /><ref name=Tesla3Q2017 /><ref name=Tesla4Q2017 /><ref name=Tesla1Q2018 /><ref name=Tesla2Q2018 /><ref name=Tesla3Q2018 />

In January 2019, Tesla discontinued the 75D version, making the 100D the base version of the Model X. The base price of the Model X 100D is $97,000 (~${{Format price|{{Inflation|index=US-GDP|value=97000|start_year=2019}}}} in {{Inflation/year|US-GDP}}) as of Jan 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tesla.com/|title=Electric Cars, Solar Panels & Clean Energy Storage {{!}} Tesla|website=www.tesla.com|access-date=2019-01-28}}</ref> In July 2019, Tesla added a Long Range model of the Model X with a 325-mile EPA range priced at $84,500 (~${{Format price|{{Inflation|index=US-GDP|value=84500|start_year=2019}}}} in {{Inflation/year|US-GDP}}).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tesla.com/modelx|title=Model X {{!}} Tesla|website=www.tesla.com|access-date=2019-07-16}}</ref>{{multiple image
 | align = left | total_width = 360 | image1=Tesla Model X unveiling trimmed.jpg
 | alt1= | caption1= Tesla Model X concept in Tesla design studio in [[Hawthorne, California|Hawthorne]], California, February 9, 2012
 | image2=Tesla Model X prototype at the Texas Capitol, Austin, 15th of January 2015 04.jpg
 | caption2= Early prototype Tesla Model X steering wheel with main dashboard {{convert|12.3|in|cm|adj=on}} digital display (left) and central {{convert|17|in|cm|adj=on}} [[touchscreen]] control panel (right)
 | alt2= }}
{{Clear}}

In an engineering refresh in May 2019, range was increased to {{convert|325|mi|0|abbr=on}} and smart air suspension was added.<ref>{{Cite web|date=2019-05-08|title=Understanding The Recent Changes Made To Tesla's Model S & X|url=https://cleantechnica.com/2019/05/08/understanding-the-recent-changes-made-to-teslas-model-s-x/|access-date=2020-09-13|website=CleanTechnica|language=en-US}}</ref>

In February 2020 Tesla increased the range of the Model X to {{convert|351|mi|0|abbr=on}} of range.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Dow|first=Jameson|date=2020-02-15|title=Tesla releases 'Long Range Plus' Model S/X with 390/351 mile range, new wheels|url=https://electrek.co/2020/02/14/tesla-releases-long-range-plus-model-s-x-with-390-351-mile-range-new-wheels/|access-date=2020-09-13|website=Electrek|language=en-US}}</ref>

In October 2020 Tesla increased the range of the Long Range Plus to {{convert|371|mi|0|abbr=on}}, and the Performance increased to {{convert|341|mi|0|abbr=on}}.

In September 2023, Tesla heavily discounted the price of a base Long Range Model X In the United States to US$79,990, allowing it to fall under the US$80,000 MSRP cap for a federal tax rebate under [[Inflation Reduction Act]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Dow |first=Jameson |date=2023-09-01 |title=Tesla drops price of Model S/X, Model X now qualifies for US tax credit |url=https://electrek.co/2023/09/01/tesla-drops-price-of-model-s-x-x-now-qualifies-for-us-tax-credit/ |access-date=2023-09-01 |website=Electrek |language=en-US}}</ref> In Germany, a general price reduction across all premium Tesla models, including the Model X, led to a 10,000-euro decrease.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cardino.de/en/blog-posts/tesla-model-x-price-reduction |title=Tesla Model X Price Reduction |publisher=Cardino |access-date=2024-02-21}}</ref>

