A series production vehicle was unveiled on September 29, 2015. It has a panoramic [[windshield]]. According to Tesla CEO [[Elon Musk]], it is the safest SUV in terms of frontal and side impact crash,<!--Check refs at:

http://www.safercar.gov/Vehicle+Shoppers/5-Star+Safety+Ratings/2011-Newer+Vehicles/Search-Results?searchtype=manufacturer&manufacturer=151 --> being more than twice as safe as the next closest SUV in [[Vehicle rollover|rollover]] tests as well.{{citation needed|date=September 2023}} The Model X does come with Autopilot as standard, and has an optional [[Tesla Autopilot#Hardware 3|full self-driving]] system. The Model X has standard a [[collision avoidance system]] that uses radar-based autonomous emergency braking (AEB) and side-directed ultrasound detection that steers the car away from threats. Tesla uses a wide-band radar system to help prevent the falcon wing doors from hitting nearby objects when opening or closing.

The Model X has double-hinged falcon wing doors which open upwards, allowing the leading edge of the door to remain tucked close to the body, unlike traditional gull-wing doors. Tesla claims the falcon-wing (modified gull-wing) doors ease access to the vehicle by having the door raise up vertically, rather than swinging out hinged at the front, which tremendously reduces accessibility. The Model X offers room for seven adults and their luggage in three rows of seating and front and rear trunks.<ref name=NYT032013 />

== Specifications ==
[[File:FoS20162016 0625 104642AA (27867778826).jpg|thumb|The Model X has double-hinged [[Falcon-wing door|falcon wing]] doors.]]
[[File:Tesla Model S & X side by side at the Gilroy Supercharger.jpg|thumb|upright=0.9|The [[Tesla Model S]] (left) and Model X (right) share the same platform and 30% of their parts.]]
The Model X weighs about 8% more than the Model S and shares about 30% of its parts content – down from around 60% expected when development began. The cargo space is 87.8&nbsp;ft³.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lambert |first1=Fred |title=Tesla updates Model X with new front seats for more space and seat pockets |url=https://electrek.co/2019/10/29/tesla-updates-model-x-front-seats/ |website=Electrek |date=October 29, 2019}}</ref>

Over the years, the Model X has been available with four [[lithium-ion battery]] packs, rated at either 60, 75, 90, or 100 [[kilowatt hour|kW·h]]. The highest performance version, the Model X Performance, goes from [[0 to 60 mph]] (0 to 97&nbsp;km/h) in 2.6 seconds<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tesla.com/modelx |title=Model X {{!}} Tesla|website=www.tesla.com |access-date=May 14, 2020}}</ref> and the {{convert|1/4|mi|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} in 11.4 seconds,<ref>[http://www.dragtimes.com/Tesla-Model-X-Timeslip-28976.html Tesla Model X Timeslip] – DragTimes</ref> outperforming the fastest SUVs and most sports cars.<ref name="TeslaMotorsModelX">{{cite web|title=Model X |url=http://www.teslamotors.com/modelx |publisher=Tesla Motors|access-date=August 23, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://gas2.org/2015/09/04/tesla-model-x-acceleration-vs-competing-suvs-more-spy-pics/ |title=Tesla Model X Acceleration vs Competing SUVs (+ More Spy Pics)|website=Gas 2}}</ref> The Model X's [[four-wheel drive|all-wheel-drive]] system uses two motors (one for the front and the other for the rear wheels), unlike conventional AWD systems that have a single source of power.<ref name="TeslaMotorsModelX" /> The 2020 Tesla Model X Long Range Plus has an official EPA rated range of up to {{cvt|371|mi||abbr=}}.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://electrek.co/2020/02/14/tesla-releases-long-range-plus-model-s-x-with-390-351-mile-range-new-wheels/ |title=Tesla releases 'Long Range Plus' Model S/X with 390/351 mile range, new wheels |first=Jameson |last=Dow |website=Electrek |date=2020-02-14 |access-date=2020-05-14}}</ref>

The company planned to offer [[rear-wheel drive|rear-wheel-drive]] models, but instead all models use [[all wheel drive|all-wheel drive]]. The standard AWD has {{convert|259|hp|kW|abbr=off}} on both the front and rear motors, while the performance edition has {{cvt|259|hp|kW}} front and {{cvt|503|hp|kW}} rear.<!-- Tesla does not state combined horsepower. See http://www.teslamotors.com/blog/tesla-all-wheel-drive-dual-motor-power-and-torque-specifications --><ref>{{cite web|title = Model X – Tesla Motors|url = http://www.teslamotors.com/modelx|website = www.teslamotors.com |access-date = September 30, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://cleantechnica.com/2015/09/23/jb-straubel-burns-trolls-tesla-horsepower-critics/ |title= JB Straubel Answers (Trolls?) Tesla Horsepower Critics |date=September 23, 2015|publisher= Clean Technica |author= Zachary Shahan }}</ref>  With an optional [[towbar]], the Model X has a towing capacity of up to 5000&nbsp;lb<ref>{{cite web|last1=Woodyard|first1=Chris |title=First drive: Tesla Model X is an awesome way to spend $132,000|url= https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/cars/2015/09/30/tesla-model-x-first-drive/73089304/ |website=usatoday.com|publisher=[[USA Today]]|date=September 30, 2015|access-date=September 30, 2015}}</ref> or 2250&nbsp;kg.<ref>{{cite web |title=Model X Owners Manual (2019.36.1 United Kingdom) |url=https://www.tesla.com/sites/default/files/model_x_owners_manual_europe_en_gb.pdf |access-date=December 30, 2019}}</ref> At the [[Speed limits in the United States by jurisdiction#California|{{cvt|55|mph}} towing speed limit in California]],<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.edmunds.com/tesla/model-x/2016/long-term-road-test/2016-tesla-model-x-range-and-charging-while-towing-a-trailer.html |title=Range and Charging While Towing a Trailer – 2016 Tesla Model X Long-Term Road Test|date=June 29, 2010|website=Edmunds|access-date=September 9, 2016}}</ref> a Model X may have 70% of the {{cvt|257|mi}} EPA-registered range when pulling a {{cvt|2,300|lb}} [[travel trailer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoblog.com/2016/04/07/with-trailer-tesla-model-x-keeps-70-of-ev-range/ |title=With trailer, Tesla Model X keeps 70% of EV range|date=April 7, 2016|website=Autoblog |access-date=September 9, 2016}}</ref>

