=== NHTSA ===
On June 13, 2017, the [[National Highway Traffic Safety Administration]] announced its crash testing results for the 2017-manufactured Tesla Model X, revealing 5-star ratings in all assessed categories, the only SUV to have done so.<ref><!--merely a relay of Tesla statement-->''[http://www.businessinsider.com/government-says-tesla-model-x-extremely-safe-suv-2017-6 The government says that the Tesla Model X is an extremely safe SUV]'', Business Insider, Matthew Debord, June 13, 2017. Retrieved June 13, 2017</ref><ref>{{unreliable source?|date=November 2017}}{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0zX3z2e9I1M |title=In Depth: Model X the Safest SUV! |date=June 19, 2017|website=YouTube (who?)|access-date=June 19, 2017}}</ref> Tesla attributed the ratings to safety-focused design, in addition to a low centre-of-gravity resulting from its [[automotive battery|battery pack]], adding "More than just resulting in a 5-star rating, the data from NHTSA's testing shows that Model X has the lowest probability of injury of any SUV it has ever tested. In fact, of all the cars NHTSA has ever tested, Model X's overall probability of injury was second only to Model S."<ref>[[WP:PRIMARY]] source. ''[https://www.tesla.com/en_CA/blog/tesla-model-x-5-star-safety-rating?redirect=no Tesla Model X the First SUV Ever to Achieve 5-Star Crash Rating in Every Category]'', The Tesla Team, June 13, 2017.</ref>

